Find given motifs

Source: R/find_motifs.R
find_motifs.Rd

Find all given motifs in all sequences and return their positions.

find_motifs(sq, name, motifs)

Arguments

sq

a sq object.
name

a non-NULL character vector without NA values, containing names of the sequences in the sq. It has to be of the same length as the sq.
motifs

a character vector of motifs to be searched for.

Value

A tibble with following columns:

name

name of the sequence

sq

sequence

sought

sought motif

found

motif found in a sequence, may differ from sought if a motif contained ambiguous letters

start

position of motif start

end

position of motif end

Details

This function allows search of a given motif or motifs in the sq object. It returns all motifs found with their start and end positions within a sequence.

Allowed and forbidden letters and characters details

Note if a sq object contains characters: ^$?=()\.|+*[] in its alphabet, search for motifs cannot be performed and an error will be displayed (with exception of sq objects of type ami - in their alphabet there is '*' letter and it can be contained in sought motif). To search for motifs with those characters, you have to replace them first using substitute_letters.

If sq objects of type ami, dna and rna, motifs have to consist of upper case letters from amino acid, DNA and RNA alphabets respectively. Use of lower case letters will return an error. Two additional characters are allowed: '^' and '$' indicating the beginning and the end of a sequence respectively. Moreover, notice that '*' character may be used in amino acid motifs, as it is a part of the amino acid alphabet. If a motif contains ambiguous letters, all possible matches will be searched for. For example the amino acid motif "MAJ" (where "J" is an ambiguous letter indicating L or I) will find the motifs: "MAJ", "MAL" and "MAI".

Detailed list of all letters corresponding to each ambiguous letter may be found at aminoacids_df and nucleotides_df.

See also

sq substitute_letters %has%

Examples

# Creating objects to work on:
sq_ami <- construct_sq(c("AGNTYIKFGGAYTI", "MATEGILIAADGYTWIL", 
                         "MIPADHICAANGIENAGIK"), type = 'ami')
sqtbl <- read_fasta(system.file(package = "tidysq", "example_aa.fasta"), 
                    type = "ami")

# Find motif of two alanines followed by aspartic acid or asparagine 
# ('AAB' motif will match 'AAB', 'AAD' and 'AAN'):
find_motifs(sq_ami, c("sq1", "sq2", "sq3"), "AAB")

#> # A tibble: 2 x 6
#>   name  sq                      sought found    start   end
#>   <chr> <(c)ami>                <chr>  <(c)ami> <dbl> <dbl>
#> 1 sq2   MATEGILIAADGYTWIL  <17> AAB    AAD  <3>     9    11
#> 2 sq3   MIPADHICAANGIEN... <19> AAB    AAN  <3>     9    11

# Find motif 'VHH' at the beginning of sequences:
find_motifs(sqtbl[["sq"]], sqtbl[["name"]], "^VHH")

#> # A tibble: 7 x 6
#>   name                            sq                  sought found   start   end
#>   <chr>                           <(c)ami>            <chr>  <(c)am> <dbl> <dbl>

#> 2 AMY26|HABP4|Amyloid beta A4 pe… VHHQPLVFFAE... <15> ^VHH   VHH <3>     1     3
#> 3 AMY34|HABP12|Amyloid beta A4 p… VHHQEKLVFFA... <16> ^VHH   VHH <3>     1     3
#> 4 AMY35|HABP13|Amyloid beta A4 p… VHHQEKLVFFA... <16> ^VHH   VHH <3>     1     3
#> 5 AMY36|HABP14|Amyloid beta A4 p… VHHQEKLVFFA... <16> ^VHH   VHH <3>     1     3
#> 6 AMY38|HABP16|Amyloid beta A4 p… VHHQKLVFFAE... <15> ^VHH   VHH <3>     1     3
#> 7 AMY43|AB5|Amyloid beta A4 pept… VHHQKLVFFAEDV  <13> ^VHH   VHH <3>     1     3

# Find motif 'DPGS' at the end of sequences:
find_motifs(sqtbl[["sq"]], sqtbl[["name"]], "DPGS$")

#> # A tibble: 1 x 6
#>   name                           sq                  sought found    start   end
#>   <chr>                          <(c)ami>            <chr>  <(c)ami> <dbl> <dbl>
#> 1 AMY35|HABP13|Amyloid beta A4 … VHHQEKLVFFA... <16> DPGS$  DPGS <4>    13    16

# Find multiple motifs:
find_motifs(sqtbl[["sq"]], sqtbl[["name"]], c("^LIV", "XXKK", "EN$"))
